Answers to questions:
1. ImageProcessor - this class intends to apply different operations on an image. There is a dependency
relationship between this class and the image class that represents an image.
SubImgCharMatcher - this class intends to match between an image and a character according to their
brightness. It uses the class CharConverter that converts a character to a "binary" image in order to compute
it's brightness.
AsciiArtAlgorithm - this class is in charge of running the asciiArt algorithm. It has an arrayList of sub
images(dependency to the image class). The class uses the ImageProcessor class to compute brightness of the
sub images. The class has an (composition) instance of SubImgCharMatcher to match between the sub images and
characters.
InvalidCommandException - this class represents exceptions of invalid commands written by the user(either
command doesn't exist or parameters that are in the right format but can't be used).
IncorrectFormatException - this class represents exceptions od commands that their parameters are in incorrect
format.
KeyboardInput - class for reading input from the user.
AsciiOutput - a class implementing this interface can output a 2D array of chars in some fashion.
ConsoleAsciiOutput - a class implementing the AsciiOutput interface. It Outputs a 2D array of chars to the
console.
HtmlAsciiOutput - a class implementing the AsciiOutput interface. It Outputs a 2D array of chars to an HTML
file viewable in a web browser.
Shell - Class intended for user interface where he can change parameters for asciiArt and execute it.
It has a dependency relationship with the AsciiArtAlgorithm so when the user writes the command asciiArt, it
can run the asciiArt algorithm and represent the result in the output he picks. The output(html or console) is
a field of the Shell class and that is why there is a composition relationship. The class uses KeyboardInput
to read the user's commands and it uses InvalidCommandException and IncorrectFormatException to print errors
to the user in case of incorrect or invalid command(relationship of dependency).
The Shell class has a data member of the padded image(composition) and it uses ImageProcessor class to pad an
image given by the user(dependency).
The shell has a data member that is an instance of SubImgCharMatcher for adding and removing characters from
it according to user's choice(composition).

2. In SubImgCharMatcher I used 2 arrays of doubles that are in the size of the number of ascii characters so
the program won't have to compute brightness of characters every time(the brightness of characters doesn't
change).
one array represents the characters used for matching and their brightnesses and the other represents all
characters that were ever computed by the class and their brightness.
I chose to use this data structure because I know the Maximum size of the array, and each character has a
unique number between 32-126. So this way, I save memory because I don't need to save the actual characters,
and the size is fixed, so time complexity should probably be better than arrayList for example. Adding and
removing a character and it's brightness using array is O(1). Also finding brightness according to character
is O(1).
I also keep a TreeMap from normalized brightness to a priority queue of characters. The reason for using this
data structure is because we don't want to have to normalize the characters brightness if the charset has not
changed. In order to do that we want to save a map between characters and their brightness. We would want to
find the closest character to an image by the normalized brightness. A good way to do that is to use a tree
map where the normalized brightnesses are keys. The time complexity is O(log(n)) where n is the number of
different normalized brightnesses. When we find the closest one, we want the lowest ascii character and that
is why we use a Priority Queue where getting the minimum character value is O(1). Removing and adding an entry
of normalized brightness and character is O(log(n+m)) where m is the number of characters used for matching
and n is the number of different brightnesses.
When dividing an image to sub images, I used an arrayList because the sub images need to be ordered so we will
know what character to put in what position when we match between the characters and the sub images. Inserting
elements to it is O(1)* and accessing by the index is O(1). We don't use find and remove in it so the time
complexity is good.

3. I used the exception mechanism in the run function of the Shell class. When the user has written an
invalid command(wither incorrect format or command isn't in the list of commands or command has invalid
parameters) I threw an instance of the relevant exception class that I have created and caught the exception
to print out it's message.

4. I added another function to the SubImgCharMatcher called getCharsUsed(). This function was needed in my
code because the class Shell has an instance of the SubImgCharMatcher that is in charge of adding and removing
characters for matching with image. When the user would want to see the characters used, the only way to do
that is if we have a function for getting these characters.








